The properties of biochar are primarily determined by its pore structure, surface functional groups, and specific surface area. Biochar produced by direct pyrolysis of biomass often suffers from drawbacks such as small specific surface area, poor pore structure, lack of surface-active functional groups, low density, and small particle size. These deficiencies result in suboptimal adsorption performance and catalytic activity, making biochar difficult to separate and collect [53,54], thereby limiting its wide application. To address these inherent defects and enhance the performance and application range of biochar, researchers have employed physical, chemical, and biological modification methods to improve properties such as specific surface area, porosity, cation-exchange capacity, and surface functional groups [55] (Table 1
                     ). Fig. 2
                      illustrates several biochar modification methods and provides detailed information on these modifications.

Organic wastewater primarily includes herbicides, dyes, pesticides, and antibiotics, which are characterized by their difficulty to degrade under natural conditions and high toxicity. Direct discharge of untreated organic wastewater into water bodies can cause severe pollution of water resources [111–113]. Biochar, with its abundant surface-active groups, large specific surface area, and excellent pore structure, has demonstrated the ability to immobilize organic matter in sewage and mitigate water pollution through multiple mechanisms, such as electrostatic attraction, hydrogen bonding, π-π interactions, hydrophobic interactions, pore filling, and adsorption of complexes (Fig. 4
                           ) [114]. Numerous studies have focused on preparing biochar from OSWs of TCM for the adsorption of organic matter in sewage, particularly targeting antibiotics, phenolic compounds, and organic pesticides (Table 2
                           ). For example, Lian [115] used the dregs of Salvia miltiorrhiza to prepare biochar for the removal of sulfamethoxazole from sewage, elucidating that the abundant surface functional groups on biochar play a crucial role in removing sulfamethoxazole. Engineered biochar exhibits greater efficacy in treating organic pollutants due to its enhanced properties. Jia [116] successfully prepared biochar using the advanced oxidation process of ultrasound-activated PMS with Acanthopanax dregs as raw material, demonstrating significant degradation activity against the organic pollutant atrazine in sewage. Shen [117] utilized Clematis residue biochar modified by MnO2 chemical co-precipitation to remove tetracycline from sewage, finding that the increased surface hydroxyl functional groups, specific surface area, and porosity of MnO2modified biochar provided powerful adsorption capacity for tetracycline. Additionally, biochar-supported microorganisms are also effective in removing organic matter. For instance, Zhang [118] used biochar produced from honeysuckle dregs to remove tetrachloride in sewage by loading Bacillus subtilis. The porous structure of biochar and the suitable nutrients on its surface played a significant role in loading Bacillus subtilis, facilitating the decomposition of tetrachloride.

The rapid industrial development has led to substantial amounts of untreated factory sewage being discharged into natural water bodies, causing significant heavy metal pollution, including Pb, Cd, Hg, Zn, and Cr [126]. This pollution not only damages the ecological environment but also threatens human health [127]. Various technologies for treating heavy metal-contaminated water include chemical precipitation, ion exchange, and adsorbent adsorption, with adsorption being particularly simple, environmentally friendly, and cost-effective [128]. Biochar, known for its abundant surface functional groups, large specific surface area, and excellent pore structure, is regarded as a promising "green" carbonaceous adsorbent for removing heavy metals (HMs) [129]. Studies indicate that biochar removes heavy metals through mechanisms such as physical adsorption, surface complexation, electrostatic interaction, chemical precipitation, and ion exchange (Fig. 5
                           ), with each metal ion involving different mechanisms (Table 3
                           ). For example, Liu [130] prepared biochar from TCM dregs like Angelica sinensis and Tianmu, achieving over 90 % removal of Pb(II) and Cd(II) under specific conditions. Ren [131] demonstrated that KOH-activated biochar from TCM dregs effectively removed Pb(II) from sewage. The activation process significantly enlarged the biochar's pores and improved its surface functional groups, enhancing its ability to remove Pb(II) through surface complexation, electrostatic attraction, ion exchange, co-precipitation, and coordination. Additionally, magnetically modified biochar, which can be easily separated from water, helps prevent secondary pollution and is widely used in sewage purification. For instance, Shang [132] created magnetic biochar from Scutellaria baicalensis residue and ferric chloride and ferrous sulfate, enhancing Cr(VI) removal capacity and minimizing secondary pollutant release by increasing the biochar's active reaction sites.
